WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:05.379 --> 00:00:07.090
DAN STONE: How's it
going, everybody?

00:00:07.090 --> 00:00:07.970
Thanks for coming.

00:00:07.970 --> 00:00:08.930
DANIEL HANDLER: Hello.

00:00:08.930 --> 00:00:10.260
DAN STONE: This
is Daniel Handler.

00:00:10.260 --> 00:00:10.540
DANIEL HANDLER: Hi.

00:00:10.540 --> 00:00:11.110
DAN STONE: Our guest for today.

00:00:11.110 --> 00:00:11.680
DANIEL HANDLER: How are you?

00:00:11.680 --> 00:00:12.943
Thank you for coming.

00:00:12.943 --> 00:00:14.526
DAN STONE: We're
happy to be here.

00:00:14.526 --> 00:00:16.610
DANIEL HANDLER: We're
gonna get you all smashed.

00:00:16.610 --> 00:00:17.735
DAN STONE: That's the goal.

00:00:18.820 --> 00:00:19.770
My name is Dan Stone.

00:00:19.770 --> 00:00:21.478
I'm the editor of
Radio Silence Magazine.

00:00:21.478 --> 00:00:23.850
It's based up in San Francisco.

00:00:23.850 --> 00:00:26.070
Daniel and I have known each
other for quite a while.

00:00:26.070 --> 00:00:29.879
I first interviewed him about
Edgar Allan Poe years ago,

00:00:29.879 --> 00:00:32.170
when I was still living in
DC, about a reading program.

00:00:32.170 --> 00:00:34.180
And then when I moved to
San Francisco years later,

00:00:34.180 --> 00:00:36.920
I started bartending at a place
in the city called the Alembic,

00:00:36.920 --> 00:00:39.300
and he's a big
cocktail fan, as am I.

00:00:39.300 --> 00:00:43.022
So we kind of solidified
our friendship across a bar.

00:00:43.022 --> 00:00:44.980
So when we were asked to
come down and do this,

00:00:44.980 --> 00:00:46.771
we thought it would be
good to set up a bar

00:00:46.771 --> 00:00:48.254
and serve drinks to all of you.

00:00:48.254 --> 00:00:49.170
Talk about some stuff.

00:00:49.170 --> 00:00:49.410
DANIEL HANDLER: Yeah.

00:00:49.410 --> 00:00:51.700
It's fulfilling a long time
fantasy of getting everyone

00:00:51.700 --> 00:00:53.366
at Google really drunk
in the afternoon.

00:00:53.366 --> 00:00:55.670
DAN STONE: He's been talking
about this for years.

00:00:55.670 --> 00:00:57.280
DANIEL HANDLER: I'm assuming
this is everyone, anyway.

00:00:57.280 --> 00:00:59.029
I'm assuming there are
no other employees.

00:00:59.029 --> 00:01:00.780
I understand it's
just is a small--

00:01:00.780 --> 00:01:01.820
DAN STONE: A couple
people missing, maybe.

00:01:01.820 --> 00:01:03.195
DANIEL HANDLER:
Intimate company.

00:01:04.800 --> 00:01:07.000
DAN STONE: So you guys
probably know who Daniel is.

00:01:07.000 --> 00:01:10.670
This magazine, Radio Silence, is
focused on literature and rock

00:01:10.670 --> 00:01:13.990
and roll, which are two
of my favorite things,

00:01:13.990 --> 00:01:16.172
and also two of the things
that this guy excels in.

00:01:16.172 --> 00:01:16.880
So he's a writer.

00:01:16.880 --> 00:01:17.960
Of course you know
him as the guy

00:01:17.960 --> 00:01:19.585
who wrote all the
Lemony Snicket books.

00:01:19.585 --> 00:01:23.200
He also has written several
novels for adults-- "The Basic

00:01:23.200 --> 00:01:26.340
Eight," "Watch Your Mouth,"
"Adverbs," "Why We Broke Up,"

00:01:26.340 --> 00:01:29.200
and this amazing book
coming out next year that I

00:01:29.200 --> 00:01:31.420
don't know if we're
allowed to name.

00:01:31.420 --> 00:01:31.570
DANIEL HANDLER: Yeah.

00:01:31.570 --> 00:01:33.403
DAN STONE: Can we name
it? "We Are Pirates."

00:01:33.403 --> 00:01:34.460
Is it February?

00:01:34.460 --> 00:01:35.420
DANIEL HANDLER: It's
called "We Are Pirates."

00:01:35.420 --> 00:01:35.600
Yeah.

00:01:35.600 --> 00:01:36.440
It's coming out in February.

00:01:36.440 --> 00:01:37.440
DAN STONE: It's so good.

00:01:37.440 --> 00:01:38.009
I love it.

00:01:38.009 --> 00:01:39.800
DANIEL HANDLER: I'll
let him compliment it.

00:01:39.800 --> 00:01:41.120
I'll say the title, and
then he can compliment it.

00:01:41.120 --> 00:01:41.730
"We Are Pirates."

00:01:41.730 --> 00:01:42.400
DAN STONE: It's great.

00:01:42.400 --> 00:01:42.900
Great.

00:01:42.900 --> 00:01:43.531
It's great.

00:01:43.531 --> 00:01:44.406
DANIEL HANDLER: Yeah.

00:01:44.406 --> 00:01:46.800
Because if it were the
reverse, it would be awkward.

00:01:46.800 --> 00:01:47.090
DAN STONE: Right.

00:01:47.090 --> 00:01:48.170
DANIEL HANDLER: If you were
saying what it was called,

00:01:48.170 --> 00:01:49.750
and I was saying,
and it's dynamite.

00:01:51.042 --> 00:01:51.750
DAN STONE: Right.

00:01:51.750 --> 00:01:52.249
Right.

00:01:54.160 --> 00:01:54.660
Yeah.

00:01:54.660 --> 00:01:57.660
So we have a kind
of strange idea

00:01:57.660 --> 00:01:59.886
for how we want to
structure this hour.

00:01:59.886 --> 00:02:01.510
We're going to make
drinks, but we also

00:02:01.510 --> 00:02:04.325
want to talk about a few
works of art that are not his.

00:02:04.325 --> 00:02:05.950
We might talk about
some of yours, too.

00:02:05.950 --> 00:02:06.210
DANIEL HANDLER: Yeah.

00:02:06.210 --> 00:02:07.070
DAN STONE: Want to
explain the idea?

00:02:07.070 --> 00:02:07.400
DANIEL HANDLER: Who
knows what we'll do?

00:02:07.400 --> 00:02:09.805
Because we'll get
full of liquor soon.

00:02:11.115 --> 00:02:11.990
DAN STONE: Tell them.

00:02:11.990 --> 00:02:13.190
I'm going to start
making the first drink.

00:02:13.190 --> 00:02:13.981
DANIEL HANDLER: OK.

00:02:16.337 --> 00:02:18.420
We thought we would talk
about things that we like

00:02:18.420 --> 00:02:20.760
and drinks that go with
it, which is basically

00:02:20.760 --> 00:02:22.870
how I talk to just
about anyone I know.

00:02:24.460 --> 00:02:27.380
And we're going to
start with the gimlet.

00:02:27.380 --> 00:02:29.130
You say you serve
gimlets to everybody.

00:02:29.130 --> 00:02:32.127
This is a good
first drink to you?

00:02:32.127 --> 00:02:32.960
DAN STONE: Oh, yeah.

00:02:32.960 --> 00:02:34.418
I haven't served
them to everybody,

00:02:34.418 --> 00:02:36.740
but I think it's a
great afternoon drink,

00:02:36.740 --> 00:02:39.750
it's a good brunch drink,
it's a good summer day drink--

00:02:39.750 --> 00:02:40.569
it's classic.

00:02:40.569 --> 00:02:41.860
DANIEL HANDLER: It's versatile.

00:02:41.860 --> 00:02:42.340
DAN STONE: It is.

00:02:42.340 --> 00:02:44.270
DANIEL HANDLER: And you're
using this cool device that

00:02:44.270 --> 00:02:46.395
looked like a sex toy when
you unpacked it, but is,

00:02:46.395 --> 00:02:52.250
in fact, also a citrus squeezer.

00:02:52.250 --> 00:02:53.350
DAN STONE: Yeah.

00:02:53.350 --> 00:02:54.350
Antique citrus squeezer.

00:02:55.660 --> 00:02:57.700
So we've got drinks
coming around.

00:02:57.700 --> 00:02:58.770
Pass them down the aisle.

00:02:58.770 --> 00:03:01.660
Those are some pre-batch
gimlets we did for you.

00:03:01.660 --> 00:03:08.163
And we're going to drink gimlets
and talk about crime fiction.

00:03:08.163 --> 00:03:10.837
DANIEL HANDLER: Do you say your
recipe for the gimlet first?

00:03:10.837 --> 00:03:11.670
DAN STONE: Oh, yeah.

00:03:11.670 --> 00:03:12.680
DANIEL HANDLER: I guess
it's right up there.

00:03:12.680 --> 00:03:15.520
Our friend Wendy drew the
drinks and wrote the recipe

00:03:15.520 --> 00:03:16.021
underneath.

00:03:16.021 --> 00:03:16.686
DAN STONE: Yeah.

00:03:16.686 --> 00:03:18.630
Wendy McNaughton, an
artist in San Francisco--

00:03:18.630 --> 00:03:20.720
she did these for everyone.

00:03:20.720 --> 00:03:22.890
If you want to make these
at home, there you go.

00:03:22.890 --> 00:03:23.390
Yeah.

00:03:23.390 --> 00:03:24.240
Two ounces of gin.

00:03:24.240 --> 00:03:26.060
I mean, there's a lot
of recipes for it.

00:03:26.060 --> 00:03:28.765
I make one slightly less sweet.

00:03:28.765 --> 00:03:30.640
Half ounce of simple
syrup, and then a couple

00:03:30.640 --> 00:03:31.681
dashes of orange bitters.

00:03:33.342 --> 00:03:35.550
DANIEL HANDLER: I just always
put sugar in my gimlet,

00:03:35.550 --> 00:03:38.697
because I find simple syrup
too much of a pain to make.

00:03:38.697 --> 00:03:39.780
DAN STONE: I can see that.

00:03:39.780 --> 00:03:40.130
DANIEL HANDLER: Yeah.

00:03:40.130 --> 00:03:41.504
I mean, I'm just
at home, lonely.

00:03:41.504 --> 00:03:43.440
DAN STONE: Just shake
the hell out of it?

00:03:43.440 --> 00:03:44.315
DANIEL HANDLER: Yeah.

00:03:46.702 --> 00:03:48.118
DAN STONE: There we go.

00:03:51.767 --> 00:03:52.600
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:03:56.991 --> 00:03:58.990
DAN STONE: We can do a
commercial for Beefeater.

00:03:58.990 --> 00:03:59.865
DANIEL HANDLER: Yeah.

00:03:59.865 --> 00:04:03.025
Beefeater, the gin Daniel
Handler's mother prefers.

00:04:07.800 --> 00:04:10.630
DAN STONE: My gin tastes are
pretty much simple London Dry.

00:04:12.110 --> 00:04:13.410
I like Bombay Dry a lot.

00:04:13.410 --> 00:04:14.650
DANIEL HANDLER: I
guess you and my mother

00:04:14.650 --> 00:04:15.470
are alike in that way.

00:04:15.470 --> 00:04:15.790
DAN STONE: Yeah.

00:04:15.790 --> 00:04:16.300
DANIEL HANDLER: Yeah.

00:04:16.300 --> 00:04:17.845
DAN STONE: What are
your gin tastes?

00:04:17.845 --> 00:04:19.220
DANIEL HANDLER:
I like a gin that

00:04:19.220 --> 00:04:21.345
tastes like you've been
rolling around in a forest.

00:04:23.270 --> 00:04:25.100
It reminds me of my
wild and reckless youth

00:04:25.100 --> 00:04:27.610
where I used to take girlfriends
to [INAUDIBLE] woods.

00:04:27.610 --> 00:04:28.810
DAN STONE: Nice.

00:04:28.810 --> 00:04:30.505
Kind of dirty gin, sounds like?

00:04:30.505 --> 00:04:33.130
DANIEL HANDLER: Oh, I thought we
were talking about high school

00:04:33.130 --> 00:04:33.630
again.

00:04:35.860 --> 00:04:38.170
Whatever I could get
away with, basically.

00:04:38.170 --> 00:04:40.370
Yeah, I like a
like-- I don't know.

00:04:40.370 --> 00:04:43.960
It smells herbal, but not like
some of them smell, potpourri.

00:04:43.960 --> 00:04:46.880
There are some gins that smell
like a scented candle store,

00:04:46.880 --> 00:04:48.766
and I'm opposed to that.

00:04:48.766 --> 00:04:50.980
I'm opposed to it in a
scented candle store, come

00:04:50.980 --> 00:04:53.290
to think of it, and I'm
also opposed to it in a gin.

00:04:53.290 --> 00:04:53.998
DAN STONE: Right.

00:04:55.501 --> 00:04:56.000
OK.

00:04:56.800 --> 00:04:59.300
DANIEL HANDLER: You're going
to shake it and then strain it?

00:04:59.300 --> 00:05:00.150
DAN STONE: That's right.

00:05:00.150 --> 00:05:00.650
Yeah.

00:05:02.280 --> 00:05:07.540
We have an extra large ice
scoop for the occasion,

00:05:07.540 --> 00:05:09.464
so we might make some mistakes.

00:05:09.464 --> 00:05:10.380
DANIEL HANDLER: Never.

00:05:13.427 --> 00:05:15.260
But we're making gimlets
as the first round,

00:05:15.260 --> 00:05:16.050
which I hope you're
all drinking.

00:05:16.050 --> 00:05:18.460
I'm going to be very upset
if I see people taking

00:05:18.460 --> 00:05:22.595
a little token sip, because my
ultimate fantasy is that we all

00:05:22.595 --> 00:05:25.035
get really liquored up,
we get into a Google bus,

00:05:25.035 --> 00:05:26.940
and we go over to
the Bing campus

00:05:26.940 --> 00:05:28.490
and we just start some stuff.

00:05:30.470 --> 00:05:31.750
I don't know what it is.

00:05:33.564 --> 00:05:34.730
DAN STONE: Missing one tool.

00:05:34.730 --> 00:05:35.110
DANIEL HANDLER: Yeah.

00:05:35.110 --> 00:05:36.416
DAN STONE: I'll wing it.

00:05:36.416 --> 00:05:38.014
AUDIENCE: You can walk.

00:05:38.014 --> 00:05:39.180
DANIEL HANDLER: We can walk?

00:05:39.180 --> 00:05:41.200
We don't need to get there--
but getting there by Google bus

00:05:41.200 --> 00:05:41.800
is kind of cooler.

00:05:41.800 --> 00:05:42.390
DAN STONE: You're that close?

00:05:42.390 --> 00:05:43.150
Because they know what's coming?

00:05:43.150 --> 00:05:44.540
DANIEL HANDLER: You're like,
sorry, we were using MapQuest

00:05:44.540 --> 00:05:45.691
and now we're lost.

00:05:45.691 --> 00:05:46.190
Boom.

00:05:47.185 --> 00:05:48.310
That's all you have to say.

00:05:50.640 --> 00:05:52.470
Like making simple
syrup, straining

00:05:52.470 --> 00:05:54.178
is never anything I
do, because it's just

00:05:54.178 --> 00:05:55.280
another thing to wash.

00:05:55.280 --> 00:05:56.201
DAN STONE: Right.

00:05:56.201 --> 00:05:57.450
DANIEL HANDLER: But you do it.

00:05:57.450 --> 00:05:57.991
You're a pro.

00:05:59.714 --> 00:06:01.380
DAN STONE: We can
have more if you want.

00:06:01.380 --> 00:06:02.750
Those look a little
small in these glasses.

00:06:02.750 --> 00:06:03.030
DANIEL HANDLER: Cheers.

00:06:03.030 --> 00:06:03.210
DAN STONE: Cheers.

00:06:03.210 --> 00:06:03.710
Cheers, everybody.

00:06:03.710 --> 00:06:04.140
DANIEL HANDLER: Yeah.

00:06:04.140 --> 00:06:06.098
DAN STONE: Is this the
first gimlet for anyone?

00:06:07.545 --> 00:06:08.045
A couple.

00:06:08.045 --> 00:06:08.300
All right.

00:06:08.300 --> 00:06:08.940
DANIEL HANDLER: Well, today.

00:06:08.940 --> 00:06:09.439
Yeah.

00:06:09.439 --> 00:06:11.300
DAN STONE: Oh, that's
what I meant, yeah.

00:06:11.300 --> 00:06:12.250
I meant today.

00:06:13.320 --> 00:06:17.771
They have them on
tap in Building 39

00:06:17.771 --> 00:06:19.020
It's marked drinking fountain.

00:06:22.760 --> 00:06:24.900
DANIEL HANDLER: So
I like a gimlet too,

00:06:24.900 --> 00:06:31.104
and gimlets are a-- well,
where should I start?

00:06:31.104 --> 00:06:32.520
So there's a Lemony
Snicket series

00:06:32.520 --> 00:06:34.470
that is out now, as
opposed to the one

00:06:34.470 --> 00:06:36.261
that was out when you
were in grade school.

00:06:36.830 --> 00:06:39.240
And this is called "All
the Wrong Questions."

00:06:39.240 --> 00:06:40.740
And "A Series of
Unfortunate Events"

00:06:40.740 --> 00:06:44.580
was my take on Gothic
literature-- on Wuthering

00:06:44.580 --> 00:06:48.490
Heights and other stories
of that ilk, in which

00:06:48.490 --> 00:06:51.460
strange and sinister things
which happened a long time ago

00:06:51.460 --> 00:06:54.580
are coming to bear on poor,
wretched people wandering

00:06:54.580 --> 00:06:55.705
around terrible landscapes.

00:06:57.950 --> 00:06:59.690
And after 13 volumes
of that, I began

00:06:59.690 --> 00:07:04.180
to get interested in noir,
in which corrupt people are

00:07:04.180 --> 00:07:06.930
wandering around
more industrially

00:07:06.930 --> 00:07:09.760
sinister landscapes, working on
secrets that probably they'll

00:07:09.760 --> 00:07:11.680
never figure out,
and being forced

00:07:11.680 --> 00:07:13.130
to behave more immorally.

00:07:14.420 --> 00:07:17.770
Which also seemed to me like
the journey of childhood--

00:07:17.770 --> 00:07:22.680
that in a typical
noir detective story,

00:07:22.680 --> 00:07:25.082
the detective is
hired to do a case,

00:07:25.082 --> 00:07:27.290
and then the people are
lying to him about that case.

00:07:27.290 --> 00:07:29.600
And then as he discovers
this framework,

00:07:29.600 --> 00:07:31.160
then they say,
lay off that case.

00:07:31.160 --> 00:07:31.670
It's solved.

00:07:31.670 --> 00:07:32.730
We told you it's solved.

00:07:32.730 --> 00:07:33.810
And the detective
says, no, I'm going

00:07:33.810 --> 00:07:35.180
to find my own solution to it.

00:07:35.180 --> 00:07:37.940
And that, to me, feels like
childhood, where everyone's

00:07:37.940 --> 00:07:39.479
lying to you about
what's important.

00:07:39.479 --> 00:07:42.020
And you gradually figure out,
wait a minute, this whole thing

00:07:42.020 --> 00:07:42.425
is corrupt.

00:07:42.425 --> 00:07:43.870
And they're like, no no no,
stay in line, stay in line,

00:07:43.870 --> 00:07:44.660
stay in line.

00:07:44.660 --> 00:07:47.110
And you say, no, I'm going
to find my own moral path

00:07:47.110 --> 00:07:49.000
in a world gone
hopelessly wrong,

00:07:49.000 --> 00:07:51.820
and live long enough to
invoke it on other people.

00:07:54.010 --> 00:07:54.970
As we're all doing.

00:07:57.140 --> 00:07:59.080
We're older than
we've ever been.

00:07:59.080 --> 00:08:00.330
DAN STONE: Yeah.

00:08:00.330 --> 00:08:02.038
DANIEL HANDLER: And
now we're even older.

00:08:02.537 --> 00:08:04.670
And "The Long Goodbye,"
by Raymond Chandler,

00:08:04.670 --> 00:08:08.970
one of the great American
novels in the world,

00:08:08.970 --> 00:08:13.070
was a focus of obsession for
me at various different ages.

00:08:13.070 --> 00:08:17.090
I first read it in high
school, and I loved it.

00:08:17.090 --> 00:08:18.690
I thought it was so sexy.

00:08:18.690 --> 00:08:22.714
I really hoped that I could
live the life of the characters

00:08:22.714 --> 00:08:23.630
in "The Long Goodbye."

00:08:23.630 --> 00:08:26.110
Not even just the detective,
but kind of everybody,

00:08:26.110 --> 00:08:29.420
getting kind of wrecked
and sad all the time.

00:08:29.420 --> 00:08:30.830
Turns out even
when you're young,

00:08:30.830 --> 00:08:31.913
it's kind of rough on you.

00:08:34.490 --> 00:08:36.539
But as I grew older, I
admired it more and more

00:08:36.539 --> 00:08:40.720
as a well crafted novel--
that the language in it

00:08:40.720 --> 00:08:43.429
is hopelessly
beautiful and lost.

00:08:43.429 --> 00:08:47.080
And I also think it's a great
portrait of male friendship.

00:08:47.080 --> 00:08:49.790
I think it's a
good book for a man

00:08:49.790 --> 00:08:52.025
to give a woman who is
puzzled about his friends.

00:08:53.820 --> 00:08:55.570
I'm sure that's never
happened to anybody.

00:08:57.180 --> 00:09:00.269
Because it is
basically the story

00:09:00.269 --> 00:09:02.560
of a friendship in which
Philip Marlowe, the detective,

00:09:02.560 --> 00:09:05.570
is friends with Terry Lennox
based on hardly anything

00:09:05.570 --> 00:09:06.070
at first.

00:09:06.070 --> 00:09:07.430
DAN STONE: Kind of a
troubled friendship.

00:09:07.430 --> 00:09:07.820
DANIEL HANDLER: Yeah.

00:09:07.820 --> 00:09:09.528
And it's a troubled
friendship-- and then

00:09:09.528 --> 00:09:12.570
keeps sticking up for
him way past all reason,

00:09:12.570 --> 00:09:14.070
but in a way that's
quite beautiful.

00:09:14.070 --> 00:09:16.210
It's beautiful as a love story.

00:09:16.210 --> 00:09:19.810
I've seen some people cast it as
a love story between men, which

00:09:19.810 --> 00:09:23.739
I don't think it is, because
the men seem quite heterosexual.

00:09:23.739 --> 00:09:24.530
DAN STONE: They do.

00:09:24.530 --> 00:09:26.250
DANIEL HANDLER: I say this
as kind of a simpering sissy

00:09:26.250 --> 00:09:28.465
myself, that they seem
extremely heterosexual.

00:09:29.057 --> 00:09:30.515
And the first
paragraph-- I'm going

00:09:30.515 --> 00:09:32.299
to read the first
paragraph out loud,

00:09:32.299 --> 00:09:34.340
because it's one of my
favorite first paragraphs.

00:09:37.230 --> 00:09:39.130
"The first time I laid
eyes on Terry Lennox,

00:09:39.130 --> 00:09:42.190
he was drunk in a Rolls
Royce Silver Wraith

00:09:42.190 --> 00:09:43.725
outside the terrace
of the dancers.

00:09:44.837 --> 00:09:46.920
The parking lot attendant
had brought the car out,

00:09:46.920 --> 00:09:48.280
and he was still
holding the door open,

00:09:48.280 --> 00:09:50.120
because Terry Lennox's
left foot was still

00:09:50.120 --> 00:09:53.500
dangling outside as if he
had forgotten he had one.

00:09:53.500 --> 00:09:56.474
He had a young looking face,
but his hair was bone white.

00:09:56.474 --> 00:09:57.890
You could tell by
his eyes that he

00:09:57.890 --> 00:10:00.490
was plastered to the
hairline, but otherwise, he

00:10:00.490 --> 00:10:02.700
looked like any other nice
guy in a dinner jacket who

00:10:02.700 --> 00:10:04.920
had been spending too
much money in a joint that

00:10:04.920 --> 00:10:09.760
exists for that purpose
and for no other."

00:10:09.760 --> 00:10:14.220
I like the way it kind
of delves you into-- it

00:10:14.220 --> 00:10:15.730
seems glamorous for a minute.

00:10:15.730 --> 00:10:18.530
Oh, he's in this car,
and he looks this way,

00:10:18.530 --> 00:10:20.430
and what a glamorous life.

00:10:20.430 --> 00:10:22.630
And then there's this
kind of seething cynical

00:10:22.630 --> 00:10:24.820
that exists for that
purpose and no other.

00:10:24.820 --> 00:10:28.230
That is, for Raymond
Chandler and Philip Marlowe,

00:10:28.230 --> 00:10:30.700
his detective, in particular
are full of this kind

00:10:30.700 --> 00:10:33.710
of constant cynical judgment
on these people who he's

00:10:33.710 --> 00:10:36.674
doing anything in the world
to help, which is fun.

00:10:36.674 --> 00:10:37.340
DAN STONE: Yeah.

00:10:37.340 --> 00:10:37.840
Yeah.

00:10:37.840 --> 00:10:39.390
Incredible tone to it.

00:10:39.390 --> 00:10:42.560
And I love how-- you do this
in your writing a lot, too,

00:10:42.560 --> 00:10:44.170
and this is something
that usually-- I

00:10:44.170 --> 00:10:46.450
remember we published a
short story of Daniel's

00:10:46.450 --> 00:10:48.025
in this first issue.

00:10:49.720 --> 00:10:51.360
Usually, you point
out when somebody

00:10:51.360 --> 00:10:53.162
repeats a word too
close together,

00:10:53.162 --> 00:10:55.120
because it's something
you're just not supposed

00:10:55.120 --> 00:10:55.828
to do in writing.

00:10:55.828 --> 00:10:58.660
And this whole paragraph
is tied together

00:10:58.660 --> 00:11:00.987
with just repeated words,
one sentence after the other.

00:11:00.987 --> 00:11:01.820
But he pulls it off.

00:11:01.820 --> 00:11:03.361
It kind of creates
this nice cadence.

00:11:03.361 --> 00:11:04.080
I love that.

00:11:04.080 --> 00:11:04.550
DANIEL HANDLER:
The fact that you

00:11:04.550 --> 00:11:05.960
can't repeat words
is something you get

00:11:05.960 --> 00:11:08.001
taught when you're writing
essays in high school,

00:11:08.001 --> 00:11:11.070
and then some people
never have figured out

00:11:11.070 --> 00:11:13.011
that they should follow
their own moral path

00:11:13.011 --> 00:11:14.510
and not listen to
the person telling

00:11:14.510 --> 00:11:15.650
them to lay off the case.

00:11:15.650 --> 00:11:16.060
DAN STONE: Yeah.

00:11:16.060 --> 00:11:16.551
Yeah.

00:11:16.551 --> 00:11:17.042
Exactly.

00:11:17.042 --> 00:11:17.542
Exactly.

00:11:20.950 --> 00:11:23.380
And then Lemony Snicket sort
came out of this tradition--

00:11:23.380 --> 00:11:24.180
or, the new series.

00:11:24.180 --> 00:11:25.260
DANIEL HANDLER: Yeah.

00:11:25.260 --> 00:11:28.865
So, illustrated by
graphic novelist Seth.

00:11:28.865 --> 00:11:33.390
I don't know if there are comics
fans in the audience today.

00:11:33.390 --> 00:11:35.404
I don't know why I
would think there would

00:11:35.404 --> 00:11:37.320
be comics fans in the
audience here at Google,

00:11:37.320 --> 00:11:39.777
but maybe some of
you know people

00:11:39.777 --> 00:11:40.860
who are into geek culture.

00:11:43.130 --> 00:11:45.900
I got Seth to illustrate
it by going to WonderCon

00:11:45.900 --> 00:11:48.796
in San Francisco, which
is-- I'd never been

00:11:48.796 --> 00:11:50.045
to a comics convention before.

00:11:50.714 --> 00:11:51.630
DANIEL HANDLER: Never?

00:11:51.630 --> 00:11:54.005
DANIEL HANDLER: I was told
that WonderCon is the smaller,

00:11:54.005 --> 00:11:58.540
artier one, which,
kind of, maybe.

00:11:58.540 --> 00:12:01.230
But I don't know what I
thought in my head, but I saw,

00:12:01.230 --> 00:12:02.620
oh, Seth is going to be signing.

00:12:02.620 --> 00:12:03.790
I'm interested in
working with him.

00:12:03.790 --> 00:12:04.998
I'm going to go to WonderCon.

00:12:04.998 --> 00:12:06.330
It's the smaller, artier one.

00:12:06.330 --> 00:12:08.870
So I think in my
head, it was like,

00:12:08.870 --> 00:12:11.670
I don't know what-- four people
in a room with a bottle of gin.

00:12:11.670 --> 00:12:14.580
And I'll go up to Seth,
and it'll work out nicely.

00:12:14.580 --> 00:12:16.580
And I walked in, and
literally when I walked in,

00:12:16.580 --> 00:12:19.560
an army of
Stormtroopers ran by me.

00:12:19.560 --> 00:12:22.240
And I had to recalibrate smaller
and artier for [INAUDIBLE].

00:12:23.500 --> 00:12:25.950
And then I was talking to
one of the Stormtroopers,

00:12:25.950 --> 00:12:28.059
who was saying, oh,
yeah, we're reenacting

00:12:28.059 --> 00:12:29.350
this battle in this other room.

00:12:29.350 --> 00:12:30.641
We have all these people going.

00:12:30.641 --> 00:12:33.085
And he said, you know,
like Civil War reenactors.

00:12:33.085 --> 00:12:34.210
And then he kept moving up.

00:12:34.210 --> 00:12:38.380
And I felt like, oh, yeah,
except the Civil War happened.

00:12:38.380 --> 00:12:40.700
It's kind of a big difference.

00:12:40.700 --> 00:12:42.760
So they're not reenacting.

00:12:42.760 --> 00:12:43.745
They're just acting.

00:12:45.430 --> 00:12:47.960
To which I have no
objection, but I just

00:12:47.960 --> 00:12:49.940
thought it was a
distinction worth making.

00:12:49.940 --> 00:12:51.930
Like, people really
died in the Civil War.

00:12:51.930 --> 00:12:53.680
It really tore
our country apart.

00:12:53.680 --> 00:12:57.190
Tattooine is fine, what
with never existing.

00:12:59.830 --> 00:13:02.542
Maybe that's hard for people
to hear, but you have a drink.

00:13:02.542 --> 00:13:03.250
You have a drink.

00:13:03.250 --> 00:13:04.855
Slam it down if
you can't take it.

00:13:06.730 --> 00:13:10.150
And so I went to him, and
he was a lonely island,

00:13:10.150 --> 00:13:13.110
if you'll pardon the expression,
in the middle of WonderCon.

00:13:13.110 --> 00:13:17.210
He was literally in the shadow
of a huge statue of the Human

00:13:17.210 --> 00:13:17.900
Torch.

00:13:17.900 --> 00:13:20.200
He was sitting in a
suit, signing copies

00:13:20.200 --> 00:13:24.560
of his very, very sad and
miserable graphic novels.

00:13:24.560 --> 00:13:27.000
I mean, they're beautifully
made, but they're miserable.

00:13:27.000 --> 00:13:28.900
They're all about
depressed people.

00:13:28.900 --> 00:13:32.760
And I think if he hadn't
met me in that context,

00:13:32.760 --> 00:13:35.980
he wouldn't have agreed to
do it, but he did, so he did.

00:13:36.702 --> 00:13:37.660
DAN STONE: There we go.

00:13:37.660 --> 00:13:40.100
DANIEL HANDLER: I think he
was so desperate and lonely

00:13:40.100 --> 00:13:43.480
and surrounded by the noise
of corporate superheroes

00:13:43.480 --> 00:13:46.600
that he was like, somebody
wants to do something?

00:13:46.600 --> 00:13:47.100
Sure.

00:13:47.100 --> 00:13:47.700
I'll do that.

00:13:47.700 --> 00:13:49.450
DAN STONE: He didn't
know you were coming?

00:13:49.450 --> 00:13:50.360
DANIEL HANDLER: No.

00:13:50.360 --> 00:13:51.550
DAN STONE: And you were
there just to find him?

00:13:51.550 --> 00:13:52.424
DANIEL HANDLER: Yeah.

00:13:52.424 --> 00:13:54.829
Well, my wife is an
illustrator, and she

00:13:54.829 --> 00:13:56.370
was on a panel,
which was a disaster.

00:13:57.430 --> 00:14:00.710
And so I said, oh, well,
I'm coming with her

00:14:00.710 --> 00:14:01.500
for moral support.

00:14:01.500 --> 00:14:03.030
And then, oh,
look, Seth is here.

00:14:03.030 --> 00:14:03.930
DAN STONE: Great.

00:14:03.930 --> 00:14:04.600
DANIEL HANDLER:
She was on a panel,

00:14:04.600 --> 00:14:06.600
and it was right when the
Walking Dead came out,

00:14:06.600 --> 00:14:08.640
and there was the creator
of The Walking Dead,

00:14:08.640 --> 00:14:10.680
and then four illustrators
no one cared about.

00:14:10.680 --> 00:14:13.400
So my wife had to just sit
there while 3,600 people were

00:14:13.400 --> 00:14:15.692
like, I have a question
about episode three.

00:14:19.000 --> 00:14:21.990
But the world of "All
The Wrong Questions"

00:14:21.990 --> 00:14:25.100
is the world of
noir, and that tone

00:14:25.100 --> 00:14:26.600
that I read you in
Raymond Chandler.

00:14:26.600 --> 00:14:28.308
I'll now read a
paragraph from this book,

00:14:28.308 --> 00:14:31.116
and you can see how
I ripped it off.

00:14:35.376 --> 00:14:36.750
Lemony Snicket is
narrating this.

00:14:36.750 --> 00:14:39.546
In this, he's an apprentice in
the secret organization that

00:14:39.546 --> 00:14:41.170
is in "A Series of
Unfortunate Events."

00:14:41.170 --> 00:14:46.080
He's about 13, and he's in this
lonely industrial town called

00:14:46.080 --> 00:14:48.450
Stained by the Sea that has
made the mistake of draining

00:14:48.450 --> 00:14:49.001
the sea.

00:14:49.001 --> 00:14:50.750
So it's no longer by
the sea, so it's even

00:14:50.750 --> 00:14:52.850
more desolate and lonely
than it was before.

00:14:55.890 --> 00:14:58.230
"I used to be that
young man, almost 13,

00:14:58.230 --> 00:15:01.800
walking alone down an empty
street in a half faded town.

00:15:01.800 --> 00:15:03.880
I used to be that person
eating stale peanuts

00:15:03.880 --> 00:15:06.000
and wondering about
a strange dusty item

00:15:06.000 --> 00:15:07.920
that was stolen or
forgotten and that

00:15:07.920 --> 00:15:09.520
belonged to one
family or another,

00:15:09.520 --> 00:15:10.978
or their enemies,
or their friends.

00:15:11.839 --> 00:15:14.255
Before that, I was a child
receiving an unusual education,

00:15:14.255 --> 00:15:16.100
and before that,
I was a baby who

00:15:16.100 --> 00:15:18.230
I'm told liked
looking in mirrors

00:15:18.230 --> 00:15:20.770
and sticking his
toes into his mouth.

00:15:20.770 --> 00:15:23.840
I used to be that young man
and that child and that baby,

00:15:23.840 --> 00:15:25.340
and the building I
stood in front of

00:15:25.340 --> 00:15:27.200
used to be a City Hall.

00:15:27.200 --> 00:15:28.870
Stretched out in front
of me was my time

00:15:28.870 --> 00:15:30.650
as an adult, and
then a skeleton,

00:15:30.650 --> 00:15:36.150
and then nothing except perhaps
a few books on a few shelves."

00:15:36.150 --> 00:15:36.660
Yeah.

00:15:36.660 --> 00:15:39.240
He's thinking about
death a lot in this book.

00:15:39.240 --> 00:15:40.240
DAN STONE: Fantastic.

00:15:40.240 --> 00:15:40.640
DANIEL HANDLER:
I think you start

00:15:40.640 --> 00:15:42.190
thinking about
death at 13, maybe.

00:15:42.190 --> 00:15:42.450
DAN STONE: Yeah.

00:15:42.450 --> 00:15:44.158
DANIEL HANDLER: Is
that when you started?

00:15:44.158 --> 00:15:45.380
DAN STONE: 12 or 13.

00:15:45.380 --> 00:15:46.510
Maybe even 11.

00:15:49.150 --> 00:15:51.110
13, I think, is a good age.

00:15:51.110 --> 00:15:52.610
I taught middle
school for a while.

00:15:52.610 --> 00:15:53.730
DANIEL HANDLER: Me too.

00:15:53.730 --> 00:15:55.450
DAN STONE: You
taught middle school?

00:15:55.450 --> 00:15:57.570
DANIEL HANDLER: I taught
eighth grade, yeah.

00:15:57.570 --> 00:15:57.621
DAN STONE: Oh.

00:15:57.621 --> 00:16:00.120
I don't know how we've never
known that about each other.

00:16:00.120 --> 00:16:02.065
DANIEL HANDLER: We both
like eighth graders.

00:16:02.065 --> 00:16:03.100
DAN STONE: That's true.

00:16:03.100 --> 00:16:04.646
DANIEL HANDLER:
That came out wrong.

00:16:04.646 --> 00:16:05.954
DAN STONE: Yeah, that did.

00:16:05.954 --> 00:16:06.830
That did.

00:16:06.830 --> 00:16:08.080
But yeah.

00:16:08.080 --> 00:16:10.290
I think that's when
that dark side starts

00:16:10.290 --> 00:16:12.160
to register a little
bit with kids.

00:16:12.160 --> 00:16:13.160
DANIEL HANDLER: Macbeth.

00:16:13.160 --> 00:16:15.440
I taught Macbeth to eighth
graders, and they loved it.

00:16:16.640 --> 00:16:17.610
They open on witches.

00:16:17.610 --> 00:16:18.180
Come on.

00:16:18.180 --> 00:16:19.337
That's like, the smartest--

00:16:19.337 --> 00:16:20.920
DAN STONE: One of
my students is here.

00:16:20.920 --> 00:16:23.470
Anne Farmer, who organized
the event-- her son Nick

00:16:23.470 --> 00:16:24.240
was my student.

00:16:24.240 --> 00:16:27.340
And I taught the films
of Ingmar Bergman.

00:16:27.340 --> 00:16:29.620
A week long class
where all we did

00:16:29.620 --> 00:16:33.746
was watch Bergman eight hours
a day, and they loved it.

00:16:33.746 --> 00:16:34.620
DANIEL HANDLER: Yeah.

00:16:34.620 --> 00:16:36.120
DAN STONE: They
absolutely loved it.

00:16:36.120 --> 00:16:37.420
Not even "The Magic Lantern."

00:16:37.420 --> 00:16:39.940
They liked the really
strange dark stuff.

00:16:39.940 --> 00:16:41.180
DANIEL HANDLER: My middle
school was about two blocks

00:16:41.180 --> 00:16:42.970
from the Parkside Theatre,
which is no longer there,

00:16:42.970 --> 00:16:44.320
but it was on [INAUDIBLE]
in San Francisco.

00:16:44.320 --> 00:16:46.280
It was an art house
theater of the old school.

00:16:46.280 --> 00:16:47.600
And they had marathon days.

00:16:48.720 --> 00:16:51.150
And I can't believe I had
the stamina to do this,

00:16:51.150 --> 00:16:54.350
but we would go-- I went to
Bergman day, and Kurosawa day,

00:16:54.350 --> 00:16:57.470
and Woody Allen day,
and Orson Welles day.

00:16:57.470 --> 00:17:01.380
And they would show
like 12 movies in a row.

00:17:01.380 --> 00:17:05.020
And she would maybe take lunch
during one of the boring movies

00:17:05.020 --> 00:17:05.819
and come back.

00:17:05.819 --> 00:17:07.560
It was crazy.

00:17:07.560 --> 00:17:08.940
Now I can't believe I did that.

00:17:08.940 --> 00:17:09.606
DAN STONE: Yeah.

00:17:10.869 --> 00:17:12.410
DANIEL HANDLER: And
on Friday nights,

00:17:12.410 --> 00:17:16.189
they'd stop making sense, and
they'd pull all the risers out

00:17:16.189 --> 00:17:16.980
so you could dance.

00:17:16.980 --> 00:17:17.605
DAN STONE: Wow.

00:17:18.569 --> 00:17:19.329
That sounds fun.

00:17:19.329 --> 00:17:21.579
DANIEL HANDLER: It was another
thing to do with girls.

00:17:22.316 --> 00:17:24.452
Besides roll around
in a forest, I mean.

