DAN STONE: Yeah.

00:18:55.206 --> 00:18:57.120
DANIEL HANDLER: So you
just put it in a pot?

00:18:57.120 --> 00:18:57.786
DAN STONE: Yeah.

00:18:57.786 --> 00:18:59.130
I put it in a covered pot.

00:18:59.130 --> 00:18:59.790
DANIEL HANDLER:
That pot is going

00:18:59.790 --> 00:19:01.840
to make everything taste
delicious for the next nine

00:19:01.840 --> 00:19:02.050
years.

00:19:02.050 --> 00:19:02.805
DAN STONE: I know.

00:19:02.805 --> 00:19:04.970
Well, it actually went
into several vessels.

00:19:04.970 --> 00:19:06.440
Like, my coffee
pot-- I could still

00:19:06.440 --> 00:19:08.635
taste a little bit of
bacon in it this morning.

00:19:09.780 --> 00:19:11.072
So you steep it for four hours.

00:19:11.072 --> 00:19:13.571
DANIEL HANDLER: We're with the
American Medical Association,

00:19:13.571 --> 00:19:14.204
by the way.

00:19:14.204 --> 00:19:16.370
Put a little bacon fat in
your coffee every morning.

00:19:17.846 --> 00:19:19.470
DAN STONE: You steep
it for four hours,

00:19:19.470 --> 00:19:21.080
then freeze it for two hours.

00:19:21.080 --> 00:19:22.620
The one ingredient
we have that's

00:19:22.620 --> 00:19:24.695
not up there is coffee beans.

00:19:27.620 --> 00:19:30.130
So it's also got a little
bit of caffeine in it.

00:19:30.130 --> 00:19:31.004
DANIEL HANDLER: Yeah.

00:19:31.004 --> 00:19:32.392
So it's like having a coke.

00:19:32.392 --> 00:19:34.314
Just going to put you
right on an even keel.

00:19:34.314 --> 00:19:36.730
DAN STONE: I don't know if a
vegetarian wants to drink it.

00:19:36.730 --> 00:19:37.459
It's up to you.

00:19:37.459 --> 00:19:39.250
There's not actually
bacon fat in it still,

00:19:39.250 --> 00:19:40.890
but the flavor of it's there.

00:19:40.890 --> 00:19:42.830
So maybe that's what
a vegetarian could do.

00:19:42.830 --> 00:19:45.100
Maybe this is the perfect
drink to get away with.

00:19:45.100 --> 00:19:46.808
DANIEL HANDLER: Well,
that's a great line

00:19:46.808 --> 00:19:48.854
to see what kind of
vegetarian they are, right?

00:19:48.854 --> 00:19:49.520
DAN STONE: Yeah.

00:19:49.520 --> 00:19:50.950
Exactly.

00:19:50.950 --> 00:19:52.846
I was at a wedding
recently with a vegan.

00:19:52.846 --> 00:19:53.600
DANIEL HANDLER: Cheers.

00:19:53.600 --> 00:19:54.350
DAN STONE: Cheers.

00:19:57.779 --> 00:19:58.945
DANIEL HANDLER: That's good.

00:19:58.945 --> 00:19:59.910
DAN STONE: It's not bad, right?

00:19:59.910 --> 00:20:00.280
DANIEL HANDLER: Yeah.

00:20:00.280 --> 00:20:01.590
It tastes a little breakfast-y.

00:20:01.590 --> 00:20:01.880
DAN STONE: Yeah.

00:20:01.880 --> 00:20:03.421
Well, a little maple
syrup, and yeah.

00:20:04.560 --> 00:20:06.262
Get coffee in the aftertaste.

00:20:06.262 --> 00:20:08.470
DANIEL HANDLER: You do have
coffee in the aftertaste.

00:20:08.470 --> 00:20:09.861
DAN STONE: Yeah.

00:20:09.861 --> 00:20:10.360
So yeah.

00:20:10.360 --> 00:20:11.830
Old fashioneds
are coming around.

00:20:11.830 --> 00:20:14.705
So we made this drink
to pair with a poem

00:20:14.705 --> 00:20:15.580
that we want to talk.

00:20:15.580 --> 00:20:16.340
We'll read it to you.

00:20:16.340 --> 00:20:16.760
DANIEL HANDLER: There it is.

00:20:16.760 --> 00:20:17.843
DAN STONE: It's coming up.

00:20:17.843 --> 00:20:18.940
All right.

00:20:18.940 --> 00:20:20.280
Want to read it?

00:20:20.280 --> 00:20:21.988
DANIEL HANDLER: Yeah.
"Everything Will Be

00:20:21.988 --> 00:20:25.090
Fixed By Love."

00:20:25.090 --> 00:20:26.790
"Everyone woke up hungover.

00:20:26.790 --> 00:20:28.450
Everyone woke up
in the wrong bed.

00:20:28.450 --> 00:20:30.490
Everyone had the wrong
shoe on the wrong foot

00:20:30.490 --> 00:20:31.365
in the wrong weather.

00:20:33.860 --> 00:20:35.470
Everyone was so hungry.

00:20:35.470 --> 00:20:36.600
Then everyone ate too much.

00:20:37.760 --> 00:20:39.140
Love me everyone said.

00:20:39.140 --> 00:20:41.160
Love me first everyone said.

00:20:41.160 --> 00:20:43.320
Fix me everyone said.

00:20:43.320 --> 00:20:45.774
Fix me first."

00:20:45.774 --> 00:20:47.440
I like this poem a lot.

00:20:48.570 --> 00:20:51.030
Part of it is that I'm addicted
lately to the word wrong,

00:20:51.030 --> 00:20:53.340
which was in "All the Wrong
Questions," because it's

00:20:53.340 --> 00:20:54.580
instantly narrative.

00:20:54.580 --> 00:20:57.410
That's just a word that I
started falling in love with.

00:20:57.410 --> 00:20:58.962
"He opened the
wrong door," right?

00:20:58.962 --> 00:20:59.920
That's already a story.

00:21:01.102 --> 00:21:02.060
DAN STONE: I like that.

00:21:02.060 --> 00:21:02.870
DANIEL HANDLER: Right?

00:21:02.870 --> 00:21:03.350
DAN STONE: That's great.

00:21:03.350 --> 00:21:05.350
DANIEL HANDLER: She was
waiting at the bus stop,

00:21:05.350 --> 00:21:06.642
and out stepped the wrong girl.

00:21:06.642 --> 00:21:07.308
DAN STONE: Yeah.

00:21:07.308 --> 00:21:08.450
DANIEL HANDLER: It's great.

00:21:08.450 --> 00:21:10.020
DAN STONE: And three
times in this poem.

00:21:10.020 --> 00:21:10.930
DANIEL HANDLER: And I was
talking to another poet,

00:21:10.930 --> 00:21:12.140
and she likes it with real.

00:21:12.140 --> 00:21:14.473
She says, I like it with real,
because when you put real

00:21:14.473 --> 00:21:16.060
in front of anything,
it automatically

00:21:16.060 --> 00:21:17.950
sounds like it's not real.

00:21:17.950 --> 00:21:19.415
Like, have some real lemonade?

00:21:19.415 --> 00:21:20.810
And you're like,
what's going on?

00:21:20.810 --> 00:21:23.435
[LAUGHTER]

00:21:23.435 --> 00:21:25.560
DANIEL HANDLER: I'm gonna
wake up without a kidney.

00:21:28.196 --> 00:21:31.070
So an old fashioned is another
really classic cocktail.

00:21:31.070 --> 00:21:34.390
Usually, if you order
it at your average bar,

00:21:34.390 --> 00:21:36.630
it has fruit salad at
the bottom, basically.

00:21:36.630 --> 00:21:39.587
It has a slice of orange
and a maraschino cherry.

00:21:39.587 --> 00:21:40.420
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:21:40.420 --> 00:21:41.836
DANIEL HANDLER:
Like the old fruit

00:21:41.836 --> 00:21:44.450
salad of your grandmother,
and then bourbon on top.

00:21:44.450 --> 00:21:46.170
To which I have no
objection, by the way.

00:21:46.170 --> 00:21:47.294
DAN STONE: It's fine, yeah.

00:21:47.294 --> 00:21:50.904
So that is the
new old fashioned.

00:21:50.904 --> 00:21:52.820
The old old fashioned,
which I didn't actually

00:21:52.820 --> 00:21:55.320
make it live up here-- we
already had it premade,

00:21:55.320 --> 00:21:57.330
because I accidentally
batched all of it,

00:21:57.330 --> 00:21:58.740
and then realized I didn't
have any of the bourbon

00:21:58.740 --> 00:21:59.720
left to make it
for you in person.

00:21:59.720 --> 00:22:00.290
DANIEL HANDLER: Oh yeah?

00:22:00.290 --> 00:22:00.930
DAN STONE: But anyway.

00:22:00.930 --> 00:22:01.720
DANIEL HANDLER: Still good.

00:22:01.720 --> 00:22:02.390
DAN STONE: Yeah.

00:22:02.390 --> 00:22:04.890
So the old old
fashioned is just simply

00:22:04.890 --> 00:22:07.840
bourbon, bitters, and sugar.

00:22:07.840 --> 00:22:09.735
And then at some
point, they started

00:22:09.735 --> 00:22:11.110
making a new old
fashioned, where

00:22:11.110 --> 00:22:13.450
they would muddle the fruit
salad-- maraschino cherries

00:22:13.450 --> 00:22:14.199
and orange slices.

00:22:16.270 --> 00:22:18.590
But this is a little
more extravagant

00:22:18.590 --> 00:22:23.090
than with maple syrup
and bacon and coffee.

00:22:23.090 --> 00:22:25.440
But this is more the old
school old fashioned.

00:22:25.440 --> 00:22:26.315
DANIEL HANDLER: Yeah.

00:22:29.120 --> 00:22:31.310
And supposedly, it's
the oldest cocktail.

00:22:31.310 --> 00:22:32.320
DAN STONE: Right.

00:22:32.320 --> 00:22:34.111
Well, they also say
that about the sazerac.

00:22:35.185 --> 00:22:37.970
DANIEL HANDLER: Plus I
just figure, you know, now

00:22:37.970 --> 00:22:40.530
some caveman was drinking some
distillation of something,

00:22:40.530 --> 00:22:42.330
and then he was like, oh,
a little grass got in it.

00:22:42.330 --> 00:22:44.410
And he was like, well,
I'm not throwing it out.

00:22:44.410 --> 00:22:46.010
I'm a caveman.

00:22:46.010 --> 00:22:46.677
DAN STONE: Right

00:22:46.677 --> 00:22:48.134
DANIEL HANDLER: I
mean, he probably

00:22:48.134 --> 00:22:50.090
wasn't that self aware
about being a caveman.

00:22:50.090 --> 00:22:51.790
But still, the
point was, you know,

00:22:51.790 --> 00:22:53.237
he was like,
distillation's hard.

00:22:53.237 --> 00:22:55.570
I'm not throwing this out
because I got something in it.

00:22:55.570 --> 00:22:56.800
And that was probably
the first cocktail.

00:22:56.800 --> 00:22:58.175
DAN STONE: It
probably was, yeah.

00:22:58.175 --> 00:23:00.370
DANIEL HANDLER: They're
like, Ugg, it's delicious.

00:23:00.370 --> 00:23:01.870
DAN STONE: What did
you put in this?

00:23:02.815 --> 00:23:03.940
DANIEL HANDLER: What is it?

00:23:03.940 --> 00:23:04.652
Tastes grassy.

00:23:04.652 --> 00:23:05.610
Tastes a little grassy.

00:23:06.780 --> 00:23:08.640
Tastes like mastodon blood.

00:23:08.640 --> 00:23:09.480
What is it?

00:23:10.740 --> 00:23:12.610
DAN STONE: So we were
drinking old fashions

00:23:12.610 --> 00:23:14.090
while we were talking about
what we were going to do here,

00:23:14.090 --> 00:23:15.450
and you pulled this
poem out of your wallet.

00:23:15.450 --> 00:23:16.710
You carry poems in your wallet.

00:23:16.710 --> 00:23:17.840
DANIEL HANDLER: I keep
poems in my wallet.

00:23:17.840 --> 00:23:20.030
DAN STONE: Show them one
of them, because they've

00:23:20.030 --> 00:23:21.260
been in there for a
while, and you can tell.

00:23:21.260 --> 00:23:22.140
This was one of them.

00:23:22.140 --> 00:23:24.070
He pulled this out and said,
we can talk about this.

00:23:24.070 --> 00:23:24.860
DANIEL HANDLER: You're
never sorry if you

00:23:24.860 --> 00:23:25.985
have a poem in your wallet.

00:23:28.939 --> 00:23:30.480
Even though this is
something I never

00:23:30.480 --> 00:23:32.720
did-- I never kept a
condom in my wallet--

00:23:32.720 --> 00:23:35.465
but I feel like
it feels that way.

00:23:35.465 --> 00:23:36.340
Like, you never know!

00:23:36.340 --> 00:23:37.470
Bring a poem.

00:23:37.470 --> 00:23:39.320
You don't know
what's gonna happen.

00:23:39.320 --> 00:23:40.180
You don't know.

00:23:43.400 --> 00:23:44.900
Because you might
need both, and you

00:23:44.900 --> 00:23:46.350
could stop at a
drugstore for a condom,

00:23:46.350 --> 00:23:47.933
but where are you
going to get a poem?

00:23:50.660 --> 00:23:51.450
Yeah.

00:23:51.450 --> 00:23:53.520
I'm not going to read
them all, thank goodness.

00:23:53.520 --> 00:23:54.270
But here it is.

00:23:55.729 --> 00:23:57.520
I'm also working on a
new book about people

00:23:57.520 --> 00:24:00.310
who are troubled in
love, and I liked this.

00:24:01.710 --> 00:24:04.500
And it has a panicky
feel to it, which I feel,

00:24:04.500 --> 00:24:07.470
when you're young and in love,
or looking to be in love,

00:24:07.470 --> 00:24:10.849
or love is over, there's
a pulsey, panicky thing

00:24:10.849 --> 00:24:11.390
that happens.

00:24:11.390 --> 00:24:12.306
DAN STONE: Yeah, yeah.

00:24:12.306 --> 00:24:14.760
The whole poem's about
getting too much of something

00:24:14.760 --> 00:24:16.520
and trying to deal
with the consequences.

00:24:16.520 --> 00:24:17.935
Everyone wakes up hungover.

00:24:17.935 --> 00:24:18.810
DANIEL HANDLER: Yeah.

00:24:18.810 --> 00:24:22.182
And sympathy for
somebody else, but still

00:24:22.182 --> 00:24:23.140
not putting them first.

00:24:23.140 --> 00:24:24.126
DAN STONE: Right.

00:24:24.126 --> 00:24:26.000
DANIEL HANDLER: Love me
first, everyone said.

00:24:26.000 --> 00:24:27.087
Fix me first.

00:24:27.087 --> 00:24:29.670
You have sympathy for, like, oh,
the whole world's in trouble,

00:24:29.670 --> 00:24:32.610
but still, my troubles
should actually be first.

00:24:32.610 --> 00:24:35.192
Which feels like a young
and in love problem.

00:24:35.192 --> 00:24:37.650
And it reminds me of the first
time I had an old fashioned,

00:24:37.650 --> 00:24:44.310
I was in my early 20s, and
I was at the first meeting

00:24:44.310 --> 00:24:47.610
with my literary agent, who
is still my literary agent.

00:24:47.610 --> 00:24:49.980
But I had my first
novel, "The Basic Eight."

00:24:49.980 --> 00:24:51.110
I'd given her 50 pages.

00:24:51.110 --> 00:24:52.580
She said she liked
it, and then she said,

00:24:52.580 --> 00:24:53.640
I'm going to happen to
be in San Francisco.

00:24:53.640 --> 00:24:54.760
Come have a drink with me.

00:24:55.920 --> 00:25:02.370
Which was-- I was so
young, and working at a job

00:25:02.370 --> 00:25:06.750
that I had no commitment to
and wasn't a good employee at.

00:25:06.750 --> 00:25:10.420
So it seemed really glamorous
to go downtown to San Francisco

00:25:10.420 --> 00:25:12.360
and have a drink with
a literary agent.

00:25:12.360 --> 00:25:13.660
And I didn't know what
I was going to do.

00:25:13.660 --> 00:25:15.040
I didn't know, like,
do I bring a gift?

00:25:15.040 --> 00:25:15.831
How does this work?

00:25:17.780 --> 00:25:22.839
So I only had one suit
and one nice white shirt

00:25:22.839 --> 00:25:24.880
then that I had to pin
together with safety pins,

00:25:24.880 --> 00:25:26.180
because the buttons were gone.

00:25:26.180 --> 00:25:26.860
So I wore those.

00:25:26.860 --> 00:25:27.360
Classy.

00:25:28.780 --> 00:25:30.300
And then she sat
down, and she said,

00:25:30.300 --> 00:25:31.424
I'll have an old fashioned.

00:25:31.424 --> 00:25:34.100
And I was like, yeah,
me too, of course.

00:25:34.100 --> 00:25:36.210
And then thinking, I
wonder what that is.

00:25:36.210 --> 00:25:37.870
And then hoping
that there wasn't a

00:25:37.870 --> 00:25:39.370
follow up question,
because I didn't

00:25:39.370 --> 00:25:40.840
know anything about
cocktails then.

00:25:40.840 --> 00:25:41.710
DAN STONE: How do you like it?

00:25:41.710 --> 00:25:41.920
DANIEL HANDLER: Yeah.

00:25:41.920 --> 00:25:42.190
Like, oh, yeah?

00:25:42.190 --> 00:25:42.580
How do you like it?

00:25:42.580 --> 00:25:44.665
I'd be like, oh, with
a wing wang wunnamunga.

00:25:44.665 --> 00:25:45.220
You know.

00:25:46.240 --> 00:25:47.045
Belgian style.

00:25:48.550 --> 00:25:49.180
Yeah.

00:25:49.180 --> 00:25:49.600
But [INAUDIBLE].

00:25:49.600 --> 00:25:50.600
They just brought me it.

00:25:50.600 --> 00:25:54.280
And it's a good drink to
nurse, because the ice melts,

00:25:54.280 --> 00:25:56.220
and everything
continues to be nice.

00:25:56.220 --> 00:25:58.260
And so if you're worried
about getting drunk

00:25:58.260 --> 00:26:00.259
during your first meeting
with a literary agent,

00:26:00.259 --> 00:26:01.860
you can just kind of nurture it.

00:26:01.860 --> 00:26:03.745
DAN STONE: It's always
a good drink to order.

00:26:03.745 --> 00:26:06.120
No one ever has a problem with
ordering an old fashioned,

00:26:06.120 --> 00:26:07.661
even if you get the
fruit salad kind.

00:26:07.661 --> 00:26:10.430
I went around the city with
a few friends the other day

00:26:10.430 --> 00:26:13.880
on bicycles, and we
got an old fashioned

00:26:13.880 --> 00:26:15.430
from every bar we walked into.

00:26:15.430 --> 00:26:16.404
Maybe six places.

00:26:16.404 --> 00:26:18.070
DANIEL HANDLER: I
hope you had a helmet.

00:26:18.070 --> 00:26:18.685
DAN STONE: We did, yeah.

00:26:18.685 --> 00:26:19.390
We had a helmet.

00:26:19.390 --> 00:26:19.810
We wore it in the bar.

00:26:19.810 --> 00:26:20.540
DANIEL HANDLER: Yeah.

00:26:20.540 --> 00:26:21.340
Can't be too careful.

00:26:21.340 --> 00:26:22.006
DAN STONE: Yeah.

00:26:22.006 --> 00:26:23.040
Exactly.

00:26:23.040 --> 00:26:25.680
And they weren't all great,
but it's an old fashioned.

00:26:25.680 --> 00:26:27.815
So even if they're
not great, it's

00:26:27.815 --> 00:26:29.690
one of those drinks
that's still pretty good.

00:26:29.690 --> 00:26:31.490
Not all drinks are like that.

00:26:31.490 --> 00:26:33.055
DANIEL HANDLER: And I would
say that's my connection to it

00:26:33.055 --> 00:26:33.555
with poetry.

00:26:33.555 --> 00:26:37.400
A, it's old, and it's being
reinvented all the time.

00:26:37.400 --> 00:26:40.420
And that I'm a big
reader of poetry,

00:26:40.420 --> 00:26:42.480
and a big believer
in poetry, and I

00:26:42.480 --> 00:26:44.720
try to be something of a
proselytizer about poetry,

00:26:44.720 --> 00:26:49.300
because I feel like if you
read poetry on a regular basis,

00:26:49.300 --> 00:26:52.880
you will achieve a calm state
that no other work of art, I

00:26:52.880 --> 00:26:54.540
think, can provide.

00:26:54.540 --> 00:26:57.180
And particularly now
in the world online,

00:26:57.180 --> 00:26:59.352
it's really easy to find
poetry really easily.

00:26:59.352 --> 00:27:00.810
Actually, through
Poetry Foundation

00:27:00.810 --> 00:27:03.090
and through Poetry
Magazine, they'll

00:27:03.090 --> 00:27:05.080
send you one in your
inbox every day.

00:27:05.080 --> 00:27:07.190
And like an old fashioned,
it's not always great,

00:27:07.190 --> 00:27:08.470
but it's never quite terrible.

00:27:09.482 --> 00:27:11.440
The poems that come from
the Poetry Foundation.

00:27:11.440 --> 00:27:12.390
I don't mean no
poetry is terrible.

00:27:12.390 --> 00:27:13.223
DAN STONE: OK, yeah.

00:27:14.007 --> 00:27:14.590
Yeah, I agree.

00:27:14.590 --> 00:27:17.090
DANIEL HANDLER: And I like
thinking about poetry,

00:27:17.090 --> 00:27:19.040
because it's really old.

00:27:19.040 --> 00:27:21.320
I write novels, and the
novel was invented--

00:27:21.320 --> 00:27:22.700
DAN STONE: It's a new form.

00:27:22.700 --> 00:27:26.050
DANIEL HANDLER: There are
different theories about when

00:27:26.050 --> 00:27:29.240
the first novel was, but
they're all not so long ago.

00:27:29.240 --> 00:27:31.835
And poetry traces back to
when people were talking.

00:27:33.070 --> 00:27:35.820
And it's fascinating to me.

00:27:35.820 --> 00:27:38.709
And the practitioners of poetry,
particularly if you put a drink

00:27:38.709 --> 00:27:41.000
in them, will begin talking
about the ancient tradition

00:27:41.000 --> 00:27:42.420
in a way that you
find fascinating.

00:27:42.420 --> 00:27:44.575
Although they're poets, so you
have to pay for the drinks.

00:27:44.575 --> 00:27:45.533
DAN STONE: That's true.

00:27:45.533 --> 00:27:46.420
That's true.

00:27:46.420 --> 00:27:48.800
Why do you think it
creates that sense of calm?

00:27:50.191 --> 00:27:52.190
DANIEL HANDLER: This will
sound kind of woo-woo,

00:27:52.190 --> 00:27:54.106
but I'm on the second drink.

00:27:54.106 --> 00:27:55.480
I think that it
puts you in touch

00:27:55.480 --> 00:27:57.060
with this very
ancient tradition.

00:27:57.060 --> 00:27:59.910
I think in reading
a poem, you're

00:27:59.910 --> 00:28:03.630
attaching yourself so
this long, glorious thing.

00:28:03.630 --> 00:28:06.160
And I think part of being in
the world is attaching yourself

00:28:06.160 --> 00:28:07.210
to something larger.

00:28:08.230 --> 00:28:10.350
And I'm not a religious
person, for instance,

00:28:10.350 --> 00:28:11.750
but that's an obvious
way in which people

00:28:11.750 --> 00:28:13.249
attach themself to
something larger.

00:28:13.249 --> 00:28:14.764
But I think even
that's why people

00:28:14.764 --> 00:28:16.430
like to work at big
companies sometimes.

00:28:16.430 --> 00:28:18.980
You like to be part of
something that's happening.

00:28:18.980 --> 00:28:24.370
And poetry was invented
to make people feel better

00:28:24.370 --> 00:28:25.084
about the world.

00:28:25.084 --> 00:28:26.500
DAN STONE: And to
remember things.

00:28:26.500 --> 00:28:28.207
DANIEL HANDLER: When
people would say,

00:28:28.207 --> 00:28:30.540
this is an old, ancient thing
that we say every morning,

00:28:30.540 --> 00:28:31.880
and it makes us feel
better, and makes

00:28:31.880 --> 00:28:34.463
us feel like we're not going to
get eaten by a mastodon today.

00:28:34.963 --> 00:28:35.875
And it's appealing.

00:28:35.875 --> 00:28:38.000
DAN STONE: I think that
too, especially coming down

00:28:38.000 --> 00:28:38.850
to talk here today.

00:28:39.860 --> 00:28:44.240
The oldest poetry we have was a
way of remembering our stories,

00:28:44.240 --> 00:28:47.230
because we set it down in
language that you can't forget.

00:28:48.127 --> 00:28:50.460
That will have these devices
like rhyme and meter, which

00:28:50.460 --> 00:28:51.430
they all did back then.

00:28:51.430 --> 00:28:52.910
So you could memorize.

00:28:52.910 --> 00:28:56.285
That was a category in the
ancient Olympics-- poetry

00:28:56.285 --> 00:28:56.785
recitation.

00:28:58.466 --> 00:29:00.590
People would remember
thousands of lines of poetry,

00:29:00.590 --> 00:29:02.548
and you'd preserve the
stories of your culture.

00:29:02.548 --> 00:29:05.616
Now we sort of do that
largely through Google

00:29:05.616 --> 00:29:06.490
and things like that.

00:29:06.490 --> 00:29:07.040
The internet.

00:29:07.040 --> 00:29:08.480
The stories are
preserved that way.

00:29:08.480 --> 00:29:09.900
DANIEL HANDLER: But even
things that I think of as poems

00:29:09.900 --> 00:29:12.380
are kind of slogans,
like no shirt, no shoes,

00:29:12.380 --> 00:29:15.860
no service is a poem
that makes you remember

00:29:15.860 --> 00:29:18.975
certain things that are the
basics of polite society.

00:29:20.230 --> 00:29:22.230
Which is that you should
wear a shirt and shoes,

00:29:22.230 --> 00:29:24.417
and then people will serve you.

00:29:24.417 --> 00:29:25.750
That's a good thing to remember.

00:29:25.750 --> 00:29:26.416
DAN STONE: Yeah.

00:29:28.630 --> 00:29:32.400
I mean, I also am a
big lover of poetry.

00:29:32.400 --> 00:29:34.650
I think probably not
a lot of people are.

00:29:34.650 --> 00:29:36.400
Obviously not a lot
of people are anymore.

00:29:36.400 --> 00:29:37.540
DANIEL HANDLER: I don't know.

00:29:37.540 --> 00:29:39.956
It's one of those things where
if you show it to somebody,

00:29:39.956 --> 00:29:41.036
everybody likes it.

00:29:41.036 --> 00:29:42.410
But people forget
to seek it out,

00:29:42.410 --> 00:29:44.201
so I like to be a
walking billboard for it.

00:29:44.201 --> 00:29:46.202
While I'm being a walking
billboard for Google.

00:29:46.202 --> 00:29:46.910
DAN STONE: Right.

00:29:46.910 --> 00:29:47.540
Yeah.

00:29:47.540 --> 00:29:49.714
I think people also turn
to it in difficult times,

00:29:49.714 --> 00:29:51.380
more than they'll
turn to anything else.

00:29:51.380 --> 00:29:54.800
Maybe music, but when
something goes wrong--

00:29:54.800 --> 00:29:56.680
like, always at a
funeral, there's poetry.

00:29:56.680 --> 00:29:59.512
Or after September
11th, poetry everywhere.

00:29:59.512 --> 00:30:01.470
That's sort of how people
make sense of things.

00:30:03.360 --> 00:30:03.860
Anyway.

00:30:03.860 --> 00:30:05.210
DANIEL HANDLER: Anyway,
I'm in favor of it.

00:30:05.210 --> 00:30:05.876
DAN STONE: Yeah.

00:30:06.750 --> 00:30:07.250
Pro-poetry.

00:30:08.325 --> 00:30:10.450
DANIEL HANDLER: You publish
poets in Radio Silence.

00:30:10.450 --> 00:30:11.408
DAN STONE: Yeah, we do.

00:30:12.530 --> 00:30:15.045
And we have a great conversation
between Robert Pinsky,

00:30:15.045 --> 00:30:16.800
the British poet, and
Bruce Springsteen.

00:30:16.800 --> 00:30:17.634
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:30:17.634 --> 00:30:19.716
DANIEL HANDLER: And it
turns out Bruce Springsteen

00:30:19.716 --> 00:30:20.860
is a big Robert Pinsky fan.

00:30:20.860 --> 00:30:22.350
That's the most
fascinating part of it.

00:30:22.350 --> 00:30:23.808
So it starts with
Bruce Springsteen

00:30:23.808 --> 00:30:25.350
saying, like, hey,
I love your work.

00:30:25.350 --> 00:30:25.420
DAN STONE: Yeah.

00:30:25.420 --> 00:30:26.270
Big fan.

00:30:26.270 --> 00:30:28.120
DANIEL HANDLER: Which is not how
you thought it was going to go.

00:30:28.120 --> 00:30:28.840
DAN STONE: Right, right.

00:30:28.840 --> 00:30:29.339
Yeah.

00:30:29.339 --> 00:30:31.326
So usually in each
issue of Radio Silence,

00:30:31.326 --> 00:30:34.995
we'll publish a contemporary
poet and something old.

00:30:34.995 --> 00:30:36.370
Something in public
domain that's

00:30:36.370 --> 00:30:37.911
sort of been overlooked
or forgotten.

00:30:37.911 --> 00:30:39.860
But yeah, in the
issue you have, it

00:30:39.860 --> 00:30:42.530
begins with this
conversation between the two

00:30:42.530 --> 00:30:44.360
that happened at
Farley Dickinson

00:30:44.360 --> 00:30:46.260
University in New Jersey.

00:30:46.260 --> 00:30:47.560
And no one's ever seen it.

00:30:48.580 --> 00:30:50.240
They won't release it.

00:30:50.240 --> 00:30:52.960
I got a bootleg of
it, and Bruce's people

00:30:52.960 --> 00:30:54.470
liked the magazine,
and said they'd

00:30:54.470 --> 00:30:56.070
let us publish an excerpt of it.

00:30:56.070 --> 00:30:58.644
But what happened in it-- and
I'll show it to you sometime.

00:30:58.644 --> 00:31:00.310
We'll drink old
fashioneds and watch it.

00:31:02.500 --> 00:31:06.010
Springsteen started-- Pinsky's
got that great poem, "Samurai

00:31:06.010 --> 00:31:08.500
Song," which is
a beautiful poem.

00:31:08.500 --> 00:31:10.250
And Springsteen was
talking about how much

00:31:10.250 --> 00:31:10.610
he liked his work.

00:31:10.610 --> 00:31:12.349
And at one point,
he just started

00:31:12.349 --> 00:31:13.390
to recite "Samurai Song."

00:31:13.390 --> 00:31:15.440
He had a guitar in his
lap, and he just slowly

00:31:15.440 --> 00:31:16.825
played a few chords
along with it

00:31:16.825 --> 00:31:19.050
as he was reciting
it from memory.

00:31:19.050 --> 00:31:23.170
And he just eased into the
"Darkness on the Edge of Town."

00:31:23.170 --> 00:31:25.630
And it was just this
mind-blowingly amazing

00:31:25.630 --> 00:31:28.760
performance, but they won't
let us do anything with it.

00:31:28.760 --> 00:31:30.840
So the people in
the room saw it.

00:31:30.840 --> 00:31:31.300
DANIEL HANDLER:
Someday, the lawyers

00:31:31.300 --> 00:31:32.205
will arm wrestle it out.

00:31:32.205 --> 00:31:32.871
DAN STONE: Yeah.

00:31:32.871 --> 00:31:33.720
They should.

00:31:33.720 --> 00:31:34.689
It's really great.

00:31:34.689 --> 00:31:36.730
DANIEL HANDLER: Another
thing I like about poetry

00:31:36.730 --> 00:31:38.800
and poets is that
rock stars love poets.

00:31:39.880 --> 00:31:43.620
And it's really fun sometimes
to watch a rock star get blown

00:31:43.620 --> 00:31:46.220
away, because they're
not used to that,

00:31:46.220 --> 00:31:47.640
or you're not used to seeing it.

00:31:47.640 --> 00:31:48.840
DAN STONE: Right.

00:31:48.840 --> 00:31:52.747
Well, I mean, song lyrics-- it's
probably more popular any type

00:31:52.747 --> 00:31:54.080
of literature we have right now.

00:31:54.080 --> 00:31:55.610
They're just poems set to music.

00:31:55.610 --> 00:31:56.485
DANIEL HANDLER: Yeah.

00:31:57.160 --> 00:31:59.132
DAN STONE: So I guess
it persists that way.

00:31:59.132 --> 00:32:01.360
DANIEL HANDLER: "Caught
Your Eye But Not Your Name."

00:32:01.360 --> 00:32:02.901
That's a pop song
I'm into right now,

00:32:02.901 --> 00:32:04.970
and I thought it was a
great line of poetry.

00:32:04.970 --> 00:32:06.511
I caught your eye,
