00:48:06.352 --> 00:48:08.810
AUDIENCE: I wanted to pick up
on your point about surprise,

00:48:08.810 --> 00:48:10.935
because I feel like there's
this tension in fiction

00:48:10.935 --> 00:48:14.952
between a surprise that's sort
of like a cheaper plot point,

00:48:14.952 --> 00:48:16.910
and something that is
surprising to the reader,

00:48:16.910 --> 00:48:19.680
but actually ultimately makes
sense with the character.

00:48:19.680 --> 00:48:21.560
So it's not like
jumping the shark,

00:48:21.560 --> 00:48:24.185
but it's actually something that
sort of advances the character

00:48:24.185 --> 00:48:24.685
arc.

00:48:24.685 --> 00:48:27.430
So I was wondering if you
could speak to that tension.

00:48:27.430 --> 00:48:28.996
DANIEL HANDLER: Well,
Hitchcock has a thing about it

00:48:28.996 --> 00:48:30.412
that I always like,
where he says,

00:48:30.412 --> 00:48:32.750
if you have a bomb
go off in the movie,

00:48:32.750 --> 00:48:34.880
people are scared
for 30 seconds.

00:48:34.880 --> 00:48:38.050
If there's a bomb
ticking, they're

00:48:38.050 --> 00:48:39.223
scared for the whole movie.

00:48:40.970 --> 00:48:43.840
Which, once you know
that about Hitchcock,

00:48:43.840 --> 00:48:45.340
and you watch a
Hitchcock movie, you

00:48:45.340 --> 00:48:48.940
see that it's always
ticking for him.

00:48:51.480 --> 00:48:56.290
And I think that you
want to shape a story so

00:48:56.290 --> 00:48:57.860
that every surprise makes sense.

00:48:57.860 --> 00:49:00.730
And there's some great
surprises in the movie

00:49:00.730 --> 00:49:02.480
here, which I won't give away.

00:49:02.480 --> 00:49:05.220
But you think, what?

00:49:05.220 --> 00:49:06.610
And then you're like, oh my God!

00:49:06.610 --> 00:49:08.660
It makes the movie
so much better!

00:49:08.660 --> 00:49:10.620
And that's an adventure.

00:49:10.620 --> 00:49:12.360
And I think, yeah,
it's the difference

00:49:12.360 --> 00:49:15.420
between a cheap surprise and
a kind [INAUDIBLE] surprise.

00:49:15.420 --> 00:49:18.850
And so, Raymond Chandler
always said, when in doubt,

00:49:18.850 --> 00:49:20.670
have a guy come in
the door with a gun.

00:49:20.670 --> 00:49:21.450
DAN STONE: Right.

00:49:21.450 --> 00:49:23.660
DANIEL HANDLER: And when
you read his lesser work,

00:49:23.660 --> 00:49:25.975
it totally works that way.

00:49:25.975 --> 00:49:28.600
You read for like 20 pages, and
you're like, I'm kind of bored.

00:49:28.600 --> 00:49:30.260
And then, dun dun dun!

00:49:30.260 --> 00:49:32.380
And it doesn't really
make any sense.

00:49:33.760 --> 00:49:36.070
In fact, sometimes that'll
be the end of a chapter,

00:49:36.070 --> 00:49:38.361
and the next chapter, he'll
be like, put that gun away.

00:49:38.361 --> 00:49:40.205
And the guy's like,
oh, sorry, because it

00:49:40.205 --> 00:49:41.670
didn't make any sense.

00:49:41.670 --> 00:49:46.340
And in his best work,
when he was drinking less,

00:49:46.340 --> 00:49:48.600
all the surprises get thicker
and thicker and thicker,

00:49:48.600 --> 00:49:51.872
which is what happens
with "The Long Goodbye."

00:49:51.872 --> 00:49:53.330
DAN STONE: Which
is not necessarily

00:49:53.330 --> 00:49:54.850
what happens with
this film, though.

00:49:54.850 --> 00:49:56.000
There are a few
surprises in there

00:49:56.000 --> 00:49:58.530
that are so outlandish that
when they happen, you're like,

00:49:58.530 --> 00:50:00.155
I kind of love that
they just did that,

00:50:00.155 --> 00:50:03.169
because that couldn't
be more ridiculous.

00:50:03.169 --> 00:50:04.710
And I don't think
we should say them,

00:50:04.710 --> 00:50:06.390
because people should
watch this film, but--

00:50:06.390 --> 00:50:07.181
DANIEL HANDLER: No.

00:50:07.181 --> 00:50:10.670
But I mean, sometime we'll drink
and watch the movie together.

00:50:10.670 --> 00:50:12.520
DAN STONE: Oh yeah,
let's do that.

00:50:12.520 --> 00:50:16.410
DANIEL HANDLER: But I think
that when things are the most

00:50:16.410 --> 00:50:19.440
outsized is when you
can look at them better.

00:50:19.440 --> 00:50:21.050
It's kind of like
an exploded view,

00:50:21.050 --> 00:50:25.360
like what they do with LEGOs
or with Ikea furniture, where

00:50:25.360 --> 00:50:28.520
they have the exploded view,
which just automatically

00:50:28.520 --> 00:50:29.100
is gorgeous.

00:50:29.100 --> 00:50:31.516
Because you think, that isn't
really how it would explode.

00:50:31.516 --> 00:50:33.720
It wouldn't explode
neatly for me to see.

00:50:34.925 --> 00:50:36.800
And that's when you're
able to figure it out.

00:50:36.800 --> 00:50:39.160
And I often think that
outsized melodramatic stories

00:50:39.160 --> 00:50:40.040
are that way.

00:50:40.040 --> 00:50:43.200
If you really want to think
about how your loyalty is

00:50:43.200 --> 00:50:45.430
if you're in love, or
you've been betrayed,

00:50:45.430 --> 00:50:50.260
or you're marrying into a family
who's doing things that are not

00:50:50.260 --> 00:50:51.690
the things you
would do, these are

00:50:51.690 --> 00:50:53.110
questions that are
asked by this movie.

00:50:53.110 --> 00:50:54.440
But they're asked ridiculously.

00:50:54.440 --> 00:50:56.440
They're not asked
like an indie movie

00:50:56.440 --> 00:50:58.660
with Susan Sarandon
as a depressed mother.

00:50:58.660 --> 00:51:02.680
They're in this context of
a terrible dance number.

00:51:02.680 --> 00:51:06.610
And to me, that's interesting,
when the story gets large.

00:51:06.610 --> 00:51:08.240
It's so ridiculous
that you actually

00:51:08.240 --> 00:51:11.989
begin to find this emotional
center to it, for me.

00:51:11.989 --> 00:51:13.530
DAN STONE: We have
time for one more.

00:51:13.530 --> 00:51:14.160
Let's see.

00:51:14.160 --> 00:51:14.660
Oh, yeah.

00:51:14.660 --> 00:51:15.250
One more question.

00:51:15.250 --> 00:51:15.540
One last.

00:51:15.540 --> 00:51:16.810
DANIEL HANDLER: Oh, I thought
you meant one more drink.

00:51:16.810 --> 00:51:18.143
I'm like, I gotta actually stop.

00:51:19.860 --> 00:51:20.590
Yes ma'am.

00:51:20.590 --> 00:51:21.902
Take the mic.

00:51:21.902 --> 00:51:23.010
Ask question, drop mic.

00:51:24.869 --> 00:51:25.410
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:51:25.410 --> 00:51:27.290
So thank you so much
for coming today.

00:51:27.290 --> 00:51:28.330
DANIEL HANDLER:
Thanks for coming out.

00:51:28.330 --> 00:51:30.930
AUDIENCE: I grew up with your
"Series of Unfortunate Events"

00:51:30.930 --> 00:51:31.430
books.

00:51:31.430 --> 00:51:33.466
I'm sure many of
you did here today.

00:51:33.466 --> 00:51:35.340
And I was just wondering--
when writing them,

00:51:35.340 --> 00:51:37.370
they're obviously somewhat dark.

00:51:37.370 --> 00:51:39.090
And I think they
actually probably

00:51:39.090 --> 00:51:40.635
shaped my worldview, in a sense.

00:51:40.635 --> 00:51:41.720
And so I'm curious as to--

00:51:41.720 --> 00:51:42.700
DANIEL HANDLER: And
you ended up at Google.

00:51:42.700 --> 00:51:43.540
Interesting.

00:51:43.540 --> 00:51:44.206
AUDIENCE: Right.

00:51:45.900 --> 00:51:47.160
Very interesting.

00:51:47.160 --> 00:51:48.576
DANIEL HANDLER:
You got interested

00:51:48.576 --> 00:51:51.760
in a shadowy conspiracy,
and here you are.

00:51:51.760 --> 00:51:53.050
AUDIENCE: Here I am.

00:51:53.050 --> 00:51:56.130
So I was just wondering, when
you're writing for children,

00:51:56.130 --> 00:51:58.296
so you knew what
your audience was,

00:51:58.296 --> 00:51:59.670
did you ever think
about what you

00:51:59.670 --> 00:52:01.336
wanted them to take
away from the books?

00:52:01.336 --> 00:52:04.800
Or did you have any
ulterior motive or anything

00:52:04.800 --> 00:52:06.440
in writing them,
that you were trying

00:52:06.440 --> 00:52:08.900
to send a certain
message to children?

00:52:13.054 --> 00:52:14.565
Did you ever think about it?

00:52:14.565 --> 00:52:15.940
DANIEL HANDLER:
I don't think so.

00:52:15.940 --> 00:52:18.315
I mean, sometimes I was kind
of forced to think about it.

00:52:18.315 --> 00:52:23.110
But I think a greatly crafted
story has a great message,

00:52:23.110 --> 00:52:27.190
and that anything that's well
made is wonderful in the way

00:52:27.190 --> 00:52:31.632
that going and viewing someone
who does something well

00:52:31.632 --> 00:52:32.590
is always an education.

00:52:33.420 --> 00:52:33.920
You know?

00:52:33.920 --> 00:52:36.970
That if you all took
a day off from Google

00:52:36.970 --> 00:52:39.140
and went to watch
the best guy making

00:52:39.140 --> 00:52:40.690
stained glass in
the world, you would

00:52:40.690 --> 00:52:42.640
learn something from that,
even though, probably,

00:52:42.640 --> 00:52:44.820
you're not engaged in the
making of stained glass a lot

00:52:44.820 --> 00:52:45.445
here at Google.

00:52:46.510 --> 00:52:49.020
And I think that
in the same way,

00:52:49.020 --> 00:52:52.310
a story that's well
crafted that makes sense

00:52:52.310 --> 00:52:54.300
can bring a lesson home.

00:52:54.300 --> 00:52:56.870
But I didn't think
to myself, what's

00:52:56.870 --> 00:52:58.990
a great thing to
teach 10-year-olds?

00:52:58.990 --> 00:53:01.650
Because there's a lot of
books for 10-year-olds

00:53:01.650 --> 00:53:05.110
that you can read that you can
tell start with that, you know?

00:53:05.110 --> 00:53:07.410
That's like, I just want
to teach about diversity,

00:53:07.410 --> 00:53:08.970
but I don't have an idea.

00:53:08.970 --> 00:53:10.172
But diversity's great!

00:53:10.172 --> 00:53:11.380
And those books are terrible.

00:53:11.380 --> 00:53:12.046
AUDIENCE: Right.

00:53:12.046 --> 00:53:13.027
And yours weren't.

00:53:13.027 --> 00:53:14.110
DANIEL HANDLER: Thank you.

00:53:14.110 --> 00:53:14.800
AUDIENCE: Subtle.

00:53:14.800 --> 00:53:16.370
DANIEL HANDLER: Well, I don't
know if I was subtle as much as

00:53:16.370 --> 00:53:19.364
that I was not interested--
I didn't think to myself,

00:53:19.364 --> 00:53:20.780
what a wonderful
platform you have

00:53:20.780 --> 00:53:22.300
to teach third
graders or something.

00:53:22.300 --> 00:53:24.825
I thought, wouldn't it be funny
if a family was thrown down

00:53:24.825 --> 00:53:26.050
an elevator shaft?

00:53:26.050 --> 00:53:28.451
And then I went from there.

00:53:28.451 --> 00:53:31.610
[LAUGHTER]

00:53:31.610 --> 00:53:33.861
AUDIENCE: Well, on that
note, thank you [INAUDIBLE].

00:53:33.861 --> 00:53:34.330
DANIEL HANDLER: Yeah.

00:53:34.330 --> 00:53:35.010
Bye, everybody.

00:53:35.010 --> 00:53:35.280
Thanks for coming.

00:53:35.280 --> 00:53:36.940
DAN STONE: So everybody,
thank you for being here.

00:53:36.940 --> 00:53:37.480
And let's thank Daniel Handler.

00:53:37.480 --> 00:53:39.896
DANIEL HANDLER: Thanks to Dan
Stone for making the drinks.

